Yes. Your new code should **accept only the current compressed format**, and when it receives an old encrypted cookie, it should **delete it and clear the session instead of throwing**.

Right now, your new code does:

```csharp
Session = DecompressString(Session);
```

So any old encrypted `ArchiveData` cookie will crash with a decompression error because it is not GZip data. Your uploaded code now removed `EncryptString` / `DecryptString` and only uses `CompressString` / `DecompressString`, so you need a safe detection layer before decompressing. 

Below is a safer version.

## 1. Add a version prefix for the new cookie

Use this:

```csharp
private const string ArchiveCookieName = "ArchiveData";
private const string CurrentArchiveVersion = "v3:";
```

Why `v3:`? Because you already had:

```text
old version = encrypted only
temporary version = compressed + encrypted
current version = compressed only
```

So using `v3:` makes the new format clear.

